ro-Blade-dst.png?resize=768%2C792&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blade-dst.png?resize=1164%2C1200&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1164w\" width=\"1164\" height=\"1200\" loading=\"lazy\" /><figcaption>This is fast, but half what the Pro Blade on a USB 3.2×2 bus is capable of.</figcaption></figure></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div></div>\n\t\t</div></figure></div>\n\n\n\n<p>As I said, it’s always nice to have a little context, so we’ve included the results from PCWorld’s Windows test bed for the hard disks in both RAID 0 and RAID 1, as well as the Pro Blade SSD. They’re compared to the recently reviewed <a href=\"https://www.pcworld.com/article/2359150/seagate-expansion-desktop-hdd-review.html\">Seagate Expansion Desktop</a> hard drive, and the Pro Blade Transport using USB 3.2×2.  </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Yes, the numbers are a bit more impressive under Windows. But again, the Thunderbolt hindered the Pro Blade on the G-RAID by limiting it to 10Gbps.</p>\n\n\n<div><figure><img src=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1200\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2396w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=300%2C152&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=768%2C388&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=1200%2C606&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=1536%2C776&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=2048%2C1034&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"606\" loading=\"lazy\" />\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2396w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=300%2C152&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=768%2C388&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=1200%2C606&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=1536%2C776&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=2048%2C1034&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"606\" loading=\"lazy\" /></figure></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2396w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=300%2C152&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=768%2C388&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=1200%2C606&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=1536%2C776&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-CDM-Seq.jpg?resize=2048%2C1034&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"606\" loading=\"lazy\" /></figure></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div></div>\n\t\t</div></figure></div>\n\n\n\n<p>The random numbers for the hard disks are minuscule compared to the Pro Blade’s. But CrystalDiskMark 8’s numbers are still valid, even if it’s not designed specifically for HDDs.</p>\n\n\n<div><figure><img src=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1200\" alt=\"G-RAID Mirror CrystalDiskMark 8 results\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2496w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=300%2C145&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=768%2C372&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=1200%2C582&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=1536%2C745&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=2048%2C993&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"582\" loading=\"lazy\" />\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<figcaption><p>This chart shows just how choked the Pro Blade is on the Thunderbolt bus. It’s still way faster at random ops than the HDDs though.</p>\n</figcaption>\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img alt=\"G-RAID Mirror CrystalDiskMark 8 results\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2496w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=300%2C145&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=768%2C372&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=1200%2C582&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=1536%2C745&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=2048%2C993&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"582\" loading=\"lazy\" /><figcaption><p>This chart shows just how choked the Pro Blade is on the Thunderbolt bus. It’s still way faster at random ops than the HDDs though.</p>\n</figcaption></figure><p>Jon L. Jacobi / Foundry</p></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img alt=\"G-RAID Mirror CrystalDiskMark 8 results\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2496w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=300%2C145&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=768%2C372&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=1200%2C582&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=1536%2C745&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/G-RAID-Mirror-Pro-Blad-CDM-rnd.jpg?resize=2048%2C993&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"582\" loading=\"lazy\" /><figcaption><p>This chart shows just how choked the Pro Blade is on the Thunderbolt bus. It’s still way faster at random ops than the HDDs though.</p>\n</figcaption></figure><p>Jon L. Jacobi / Foundry</p></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div></div>\n\t\t</div></figure><p>Jon L. Jacobi / Foundry</p></div>\n\n\n\n<p>Again, the Pro Blade Transport’s results are included to show you what these modules can do at 20Gbps on a real 3.2×2 bus, and just how choked the Pro Blade on the G-RAID Mirror is by the Thunderbolt 3 bus. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The results for the Transport on the Mac are identical to those for the port embedded on the G-RAID Mirror. </p>\n\n\n<div><figure><img src=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1200\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2434w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=300%2C150&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=768%2C384&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=1200%2C600&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=1536%2C767&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=2048%2C1023&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"600\" loading=\"lazy\" />\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<figcaption>In RAID 0 the G-RAID Mirror beat the Seagate, but lost in the safer RAID 1 mode.</figcaption>\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2434w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=300%2C150&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=768%2C384&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=1200%2C600&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=1536%2C767&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=2048%2C1023&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"600\" loading=\"lazy\" /><figcaption>In RAID 0 the G-RAID Mirror beat the Seagate, but lost in the safer RAID 1 mode.</figcaption></figure></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2434w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=300%2C150&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=768%2C384&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=1200%2C600&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=1536%2C767&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-48GB.jpg?resize=2048%2C1023&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"600\" loading=\"lazy\" /><figcaption>In RAID 0 the G-RAID Mirror beat the Seagate, but lost in the safer RAID 1 mode.</figcaption></figure></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div></div>\n\t\t</div></figure></div>\n\n\n\n<p>Obviously, once again, the G-RAID Mirror in RAID 0 was way faster writing 450GB than RAID 1. </p>\n\n\n<div><figure><img src=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1200\" alt=\"G-RAID Mirror 450GB\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2498w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=300%2C146&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=768%2C374&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=1200%2C584&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=1536%2C748&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=2048%2C997&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"584\" loading=\"lazy\" />\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<figcaption><p>The G-RAID Mirror took a while to write 450GB, as all hard drives will.</p> </figcaption>\t\t<div>\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img alt=\"G-RAID Mirror 450GB\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2498w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=300%2C146&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=768%2C374&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=1200%2C584&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=1536%2C748&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=2048%2C997&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"584\" loading=\"lazy\" /><figcaption><p>The G-RAID Mirror took a while to write 450GB, as all hard drives will.</p> </figcaption></figure><p>Jon L. Jacobi</p></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div><div><figure><img alt=\"G-RAID Mirror 450GB\" srcset=\"https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?quality=50&amp;strip=all 2498w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=300%2C146&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 300w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=768%2C374&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 768w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=1200%2C584&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1200w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=1536%2C748&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 1536w, https://b2c-contenthub.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/G-RAID-Mirror-450GB-1.jpg?resize=2048%2C997&amp;quality=50&amp;strip=all 2048w\" width=\"1200\" height=\"584\" loading=\"lazy\" /><figcaption><p>The G-RAID Mirror took a while to write 450GB, as all hard drives will.</p> </figcaption></figure><p>Jon L. Jacobi</p></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div></div>\n\t\t</div></figure><p>Jon L. Jacobi</p></div>\n\n\n\n<p>The G-RAID Mirror’s fan, when it kicks in at startup is rather loud. Most of the time, however, my Mac Studio fan makes as much noise, and that’s hardly any. To be fair, my office has test beds and NAS boxes whirring away most of the time, so my tolerance for white noise is very high. But there’s also noise due the read/write heads moving about. If you haven’t been around hard drives for a while, it might bug you. One might argue for more sound-deadening material inside, but that tends to trap heat as well noise, and that would be bad.  </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Note that the user guide I downloaded says you only have to turn off the G-RAID Mirror twice when changing RAID modes, which one might interpret as using the power button. This would be wrong. Info on the website and my experience says you must<a href=\"https://support-en.wd.com/app/answers/detailweb/a_id/51098/kw/G-RAID%20Mirror%20RAID\"> pull the power plug both times to switch RAID modes</a>. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>In total, the G-RAID Mirror is a lot faster in RAID 0 than RAID 1, which means you might be better off with two less capacious models using RAID 0 and macOS’s own RAID 1 mode. Then again, you could employ the Pro Blade when you need real speed, and leave the HDDs safely mirrored.</p>\n\n\n\n<div><div>\n<h2>Should you buy the SanDisk Professional G-RAID Mirror?</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The G-RAID Mirror is an appealing storage product, especially for videographers. It’s handsome, speedy for a hard drive, and best of all, fantastically capacious. Throw in the Pro Blade port, even if it is running at half speed, and you have an extremely useful, albeit pricey solution for super-large data sets.  </p>\n\n\n\n<p>But come on SanDisk, USB 4, USB 4…</p>\n</div></div>\n\n</div>","author":"","siteTitle":"Macworld","siteHash":"37e84dd5a21fa961d6d6630e269546024dbb7741b2e2fadbe74f47383c70dfbb","entryHash":"e9e0c50047d725630a96f9e8e7dea955bb4755c79105efd2d5ffaec84ea79e54","category":"Apple"}